[2] Adolescent COVID
Date: Fri 8 Oct 2021
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) [edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2021/10/adolescent-covid-19-vaccinations-lag-across-us


Only 47% of the United States' 12 to 17 year olds are vaccinated against COVID-19, and in 9 states, less than one-third of eligible teens are vaccinated. The statistics, as reported by CNN, demonstrate the geographical gaps in vaccination seen in the country: Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, South Carolina, and Tennessee in the South have less than 30% of adolescents vaccinated, as do North Dakota, West Virginia, and Wyoming (https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/08/health/us-coronavirus-friday/index.html).

Across the country, 76.2% of Americans 12 and older (the group that is eligible) have received at least one dose of vaccine and 65.8% are fully vaccinated, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). Among adults, 78.0% have received at least one shot and 67.6% are fully vaccinated. The agency's COVID Data Tracker shows 56.2% of Americans are fully vaccinated against COVID-19, 65.1% have received at least one dose, and 3.6% have received a booster shot (https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#vaccinations_vacc-total-admin-rate-total).

Also today [8 Oct 2021], CDC announced that the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP) will meet on 2 and 3 Nov 2021 to discuss use of the Pfizer vaccine in children ages 5-11, following a Food and Drug Administration meeting on 26 Oct 2021.

Racial COVID gap closing
------------------------
The United States reported 100 083 new COVID-19 cases yesterday [7 Oct 2021] and 2392 deaths, according to the Johns Hopkins COVID-19 tracker (https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/data/cumulative-cases). The 7-day average of new daily cases is 99 669, with 1765 daily deaths, according to the New York Times tracker (https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/us/covid-cases.html).

Throughout the pandemic, stark racial disparities have been seen across the United States, but as the 4th surge caused by the delta (B1617.2) variant hit the country this summer [2021], that gap closed as more rural communities saw increased viral activity. In these communities, White people remain unvaccinated, while more Black and Hispanic people are getting vaccinated against COVID-19.

According to the Kaiser Family Foundation, as of September 2021, "Racial disparities in cases and death rates have narrowed for Black and Hispanic people in the recent period compared to earlier in the pandemic" (https://www.kff.org/racial-equity-and-health-policy/issue-brief/covid-19-cases-and-deaths-by-race-ethnicity-current-data-and-changes-over-time/).

Black and Hispanic Americans were also more likely to be exposed to the virus during earlier waves of the pandemic, as they were more likely to have front-line jobs that did not allow them to work from home. Now, as many Americans return back to work, essential workers are not the only group at risk.

80% of CFOs support vaccine mandates
------------------------------------
A survey of corporate leaders shows that 80% of US chief financial officers (CFOs) support vaccine mandates, according to CNBC. The survey comes the day after President Joe Biden's visit to Chicago, where he congratulated companies already using vaccine requirements (https://www.cnbc.com/2021/10/08/as-covid-fears-in-c-suite-spike-big-companies-back-vaccine-mandates.html). Only 15% of CFOs polled said they totally oppose mandates.

[byline: Stephanie Soucheray]

--
communicated by:
Mary Marshall

[It's good to see the racial gap closing between Black and Hispanic people and Whites, but it is not because the root cause of the earlier disparities has been addressed. That is, broadly speaking, essential workers had no option but to go to work and become exposed to SARS-CoV-2, while white-collar workers were more often able to work safely from home. - Mod.LK]

